mixed clustering

Based off of: https://www.r-bloggers.com/clustering-mixed-data-types-in-r/

library(Rtsne) # for t-SNE plot
library(ggplot2) # for visualization

set.seed(1680) # for reproducibility

driver_attributes <- read_csv("data/driver_attributes_complete.csv")
Parsed with column specification:
cols(
  driver_id = [31mcol_character()[39m,
  quit_within_90_days = [33mcol_logical()[39m,
  average_earnings_per_ride = [32mcol_double()[39m,
  number_of_rides_given = [32mcol_double()[39m,
  scaled_average_eagerness = [32mcol_double()[39m,
  scaled_average_response_time_ranking = [32mcol_double()[39m,
  average_prime_time_weighted_by_ride_duration = [32mcol_double()[39m
)
driver_attributes <- driver_attributes %>% remove_rownames %>% column_to_rownames(var="driver_id")
gower_dist <- daisy(driver_attributes,
                    metric = "gower",
                    type = list(logratio = 3))
setting 'logical' variable 1 to type 'asymm'
summary(gower_dist)
349866 dissimilarities, summarized :
    Min.  1st Qu.   Median     Mean  3rd Qu.     Max. 
0.005069 0.115700 0.211280 0.207010 0.290990 0.620270 
Metric :  mixed ;  Types = A, I, I, I, I, I 
Number of objects : 837
gower_mat <- as.matrix(gower_dist)

#most similar pair
driver_attributes[
  which(gower_mat == min(gower_mat[gower_mat != min(gower_mat)]),
        arr.ind = TRUE)[1, ], ]

#most dissimilar pair
driver_attributes[
  which(gower_mat == max(gower_mat[gower_mat != max(gower_mat)]),
        arr.ind = TRUE)[1, ], ]
# Calculate silhouette width for many k using PAM

sil_width <- c(NA)

for(i in 2:10){
  
  pam_fit <- pam(gower_dist,
                 diss = TRUE,
                 k = i)
  
  sil_width[i] <- pam_fit$silinfo$avg.width
  
}

# Plot sihouette width (higher is better)

plot(1:10, sil_width,
     xlab = "Number of clusters",
     ylab = "Silhouette Width")
lines(1:10, sil_width)

plot peaks at 2, so 2 clusters are recommended

pam_fit <- pam(gower_dist, diss = TRUE, k = 2)

pam_results <- driver_attributes %>%
  mutate(cluster = pam_fit$clustering) %>%
  group_by(cluster) %>%
  do(the_summary = summary(.))
